data.message: 10. Remember Drawback #1 ("I don't want to have withdrawal symptoms") from yesterday’s post? Which one of our following comebacks works for you? #balance  -Some withdrawal symptoms are actually signs that my body is healing -I may be coughing more because the cilia (hair-like structures that line my lungs and clean the air I breathe) that were paralyzed by the cigarette smoke are starting to work again, which makes me temporarily cough more -I may have tingling in my arms and legs because my circulation is improving
I would say that the first one works for me. I love to remind myself that even though I'll be suffering it'll be worth it in the long haul!!
The fight to quit will be worth a better healthier life
Very well said. :) -Kat from tsp

12. Did you know that the number of non-smokers affected by second hand smoke is more than double the number of actual smokers in the U.S.? Who is affected by your second hand smoke?. #smokingaffectsall
Just thinkin that my little nephew is affected more than i am by smoking breaks my heart.and gives me the courage to quit
My boyfriend has never picked up a cigarette his whole life and he hates to see me destroy my body. Not to mention I'm hurting him too
Sometimes taking a step back is the best way to realize our smoking addiction greatly affects those around us! Even though we are the only ones taking a puff, other people's well beings are at stake.

11. Everyone wants to know whether electronic cigarettes can help smokers quit. Unfortunately, studies are showing that they are not any more effective than a placebo. So health professionals still recommend using well-studied strategies like counseling or nicotine replacement therapies (patch, gum) when you’re ready to quit. #ecig
Lately ive been chewing more gum n it has helped with smoking less alot
No e cigs! They're dangerous and are just a trigger for me for the real deal!
3. How would you support someone who tells you they want to quit smoking? #motivation

Don't smoke around them, encourage them as much as you can! It is so hard to stop when someone smokes around you. That's why i started back up last time because someone was constantly smoking around me! Be helpful and encouraging!
Lead by example show them u are quiting as well most people tend to follow what other people are doing they dont wanna feel left out how ever it could go both ways
great ideas! Agreed that showing support and respect for their efforts to quit is great. Thank you for sharing!
I would not smoke around them and remind them each day they didn't smoke that they are doing great and encourage them to keep up the great work
Id try not to smoke around them

9. Research shows that emphasizing the benefits of quitting over the drawbacks helps smokers quit their habit for good. Try your hand at making a negative a positive. What’s your comeback for this drawback? #balance
The symptoms could be your body healing think positive

Welcome to the Tobacco Status Project! Thank you for joining us -- we're so excited to have you here. We will start posting TOMORROW at 12 noon PDT! Here's how it works: We will share one post everyday for 90 days. Remember to turn on your notifications and check this page daily!Your group has been randomly assigned to a Monthly Incentive. To earn money, you must comment on ALL posts we share each month (30 days). You will earn $30 if you've commented on all 30 posts, and $0 if you haven't. We'll tally your comments every 30 days, and you'll have a new chance to earn money at the start of the next month. You will receive a gift card for the money you've earned at the end of the 90-day program.Dr. Johannes Thrul will be joining us for 1 hour each week, during which he will answer any tobacco-related questions, share info and resources, and provide support to our group. Stay tuned for his first session next week!
I'm super excited! Looking forward to saving my life and money!!
I'm so glad I found this study

Hello TSP members! While we wait for more people to join us, we want you to know that this secret group is a great place to share your thoughts and engage in conversation. Please feel free to like or respond to each others' comments and share any relevant content of your own.To begin, let's take a moment to introduce ourselves and get to know each other a little better. Feel free to share with us:• Where you come from• Anything about your smoking (how much, how often, when you first started, etc.)• What you hope to gain from participating in the Tobacco Study ProjectThank you! We hope you're as excited as we are!
Hello my name is 10323 I smoke 3 packs a week , I would like to quite smoking and hopefully this study helps
I know stopping smoking is not easy. How confident are you that you could quit smoking if you tried? #TDII
Not very confident
Thanks for sharing 10304. On a scale from 1 (least) to 10 (most) confident, where do you think you are?
About a five
Ok, so that's right in the middle. Why is it a 5 and not a 1 for example?
Because I can stop for a couple days but soon as I smell one I need one

10304, it's great that you are already able to go for a couple of days without having one - this really shows you that you can do it and your body doesn't really need the nicotine. It's also quite normal that there are some triggers that make it really hard to not smoke. What could you do in these situations, where you smell smoke, but don't want to smoke again?
Sorry I've got to run. Talk to you next week!

8. Here are some things to help you maintain your awesome physique when you stop smoking. Which one seems the most helpful? #balance  -Make sure you have a well-balanced diet -Chew sugarless gum when you want something sweet -Eat slowly -Plan healthy, low-fat and low-calorie snacks into your day -Watch portion sizes -Read food labels
I always eat small portions guess that's why I'm a small smoker

I have been speaking a lot with my therapist about quitting and we have decided I should set a quit date. I got some patches from my doctor and have decided i will quit the 3rd of July! Would anyone like to quit with me? Just start a date!a week or two in advance so you can prep yourself and not procrastinate! Good luck!
What a huge decision -- Congratulations!!! We are so proud of you :)

7. Weight gain is one of the top concerns for almost every smoker. We’ve made a list of some tips that can help keep your weight on track while you quit. Pick the one sounds good to you. How could you implement it into your life? #balance  -Go for a walk, swim, bike ride or any exercise you enjoy -Find small ways to be more active, like taking the stairs instead of the elevator or parking a little farther away -Find alternatives to snacking, like calling a friend -Drink some extra water
I haven't really experienced weight gain but I do drink alot of water
The weight gain would be worth it for me .
5. Many e-cig companies are actually owned by BIG TOBACCO companies. What do you think their motives are? To have you remain a loyal customer? To help you quit smoking? Other ideas? #ecig
They jus want the money they don't care bout your health

All they want is your money. E cigs are just as bad and have read many articles on them getting overheated and burning people while they're in pockets or close to your skin. Please be careful if you're trying the alternative!
6. What would be the best-case scenario if you quit smoking? #balance
My son doesn't need to know I smoked

My daughter won't have to worry about having problems breathing because of her mother. Or being made fun of for smelling like smoke like i was in school. I want to be healthy and be able to care for her in my best health!
It seems like not wanting our children to experience complications because of their parents smoking is a common theme. This is a super valid and important point, thank you for sharing! -Kat from tsp
If I have kids I'd definitely stop smoking

data.message: Hi everyone and welcome to TSP! I am available for the next hour. Let me know if you have any questions! #TDII
Do u think it is wise to quit smoking and a drug addiction at the same time ?
Hi 10298 - that's a great question! I think it may be a good idea, since smoking and other drug use often go together. What is your experience?
Sorry, I've got to run. I'll check in with you next week. See ya!

Hi, I'm kind of late. But I'm currently 7 months pregnant and am hoping to quit. My hormones have been off the charts and i have almost doubled my smoking habit. I was trying to slow down, but it just didn't work out that way. I have heard that completely stopping could harm my baby girl. Is that a myth? Is it safe or would i be better off just cutting down as much as possible? Thanks!
Johannes Thrul

10334-Cutting down would be the safest thing for the child , since you've been smoking your whole pregnancy , the baby will also be going threw nicotine withdrawal and you will stress your baby out if quit completely.
Thank you. I just feel so awful, I wish i would've started sooner but things just didn't go that way. Thank you

Hi 10334 - continuing to smoke at any level is definitely NOT safe for your baby and quitting completely is the single best thing you can do at any point during your pregnancy. Please check out these resources: http://women.smokefree.gov/9-myths-about-smoking-pregnancy.aspx I will hold the next TDII session on Wednesday and we can discuss more in detail what kind of quit plan may work for you. If you want to use stop smoking medication such as nicotine replacement therapy (this is an option during pregnancy and will help reduce your withdrawal) you should definitely talk to your doctor about it!

You've made your plan and prepared for what's ahead. On your Quit Day, remember to take things one day at a time. Slow and steady wins the race!
After smoking your last cigarette the night before your Quit Day, take a shower, wash your hair, and brush your teeth. Get rid of all the last traces of nicotine!
I can't wait to do this one! I absolutely hate smelling like smoke!
The night before your Quit Day, make sure you've gotten rid of all your cigarettes, lighters, matches and ashtrays from your car and home.

The night before your Quit Day, put together a non-smoker survival kit, complete with sugarless gum/candy, toothpicks, other substitutes for smoking, a list of your reasons for quitting, and phone numbers/photos of your support people.
The night before your Quit Day, reflect on the fact that tomorrow will be your first day free from cigarette addiction!
